	- *Shared mechanisms (fibromyalgia, ME/CFS, Long COVID) integration partial* ([Chapter 3, fibromyalgia section expanded with 2 hypothesis environments; Chapter 3, dizziness section expanded with dysautonomia subsection and achievement environment; Chapter 5, subgroups section expanded with overlap-based subgroups; Chapter 5, trigger mechanisms section expanded with biological convergence and terrain+trigger hypothesis; Appendix H, 10 new annotated entries; references.bib, 10 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 3 new entries]): Partial integration of Dr. Rémy Honoré's clinical review (May 2026) synthesizing evidence that fibromyalgia, ME/CFS, and Long COVID share core biological mechanisms. Added neuroinflammation hypothesis (certainty 0.55, reduced from 0.70 after adversarial review) with microglial activation via TSPO PET evidence; central sensitization hypothesis (certainty 0.70) demonstrating shared pain amplification across conditions; terrain+trigger model (certainty 0.60) for post-infectious ME/CFS with pre-existing vulnerability factors. Added overlap statistics (30-50% Long COVID meets ME/CFS criteria, 20-70% fibromyalgia presents ME/CFS-compatible picture) with explicit limitation noting wide range reflects heterogeneity. Created dysautonomia subsection with POTS prevalence data (20-40% Long COVID, 25-50% ME/CFS, \u{3e}30% fibromyalgia) and objective autonomic testing achievement environment. Fixed critical compilation issues (duplicate section, missing bibliography entry, broken cross-references) and 3 adversarial review findings (safety warnings for speculative permanent function loss, certainty calibration for neuroinflammation, overlap range clarification). Phase 4 integration partial (44 brainstorming ideas remain); Phase 6 adversarial review partial (18 findings remain for follow-up session). Created hypothesis subtree with 4 nodes; brainstorm file with 50 ideas across 9 categories. _Motivated by:_ @Honore2026sharedMechanisms — clinical review establishing shared mechanisms across fibromyalgia, ME/CFS, and Long COVID; @Albrecht2019neuroinflammationFM — PET imaging showing activated microglia in fibromyalgia; @Meeus2007centralSensitizationCFS — QST demonstrating central sensitization in ME/CFS; @Eldokla2022autonomicLongCOVID — POTS prevalence and autonomic testing in Long COVID; @Wong2021LongCOVIDMECFS — systematic review of Long COVID ME/CFS overlap.

	- *Connective tissue disorders integration* ([Chapter 13, new section with 1 hypothesis environment; Chapter 14a, new section with 1 hypothesis environment; Chapter 14k, new subsection with dysautonomia prevalence data; Chapter 27, 2 new proposals: HIF-1alpha-ECM coupled model extension (0.55), connective tissue cumulative strain/PEM threshold model (0.55); Chapter 28, 1 new proposal: mast cell-ECM positive feedback bistable model (0.50); Chapter 30, 2 new proposals: multi-compartment ECM turnover model with tissue-specific parameters (0.45), HIF-1alpha-mitochondria-ECM triad cross-reference integration (0.45); Chapter 31, 1 new speculation: ECM degradation temporal trajectory in ME/CFS disease progression (0.40); Chapter 32, 1 new proposal: sigmoid CCI-orthostatic severity model (0.40); Appendix H, 10 new annotated entries; references.bib, 10 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 2 new entries]): Integration of connective tissue disorders (CTDs) in ME/CFS, focusing on bidirectional relationship with ME/CFS pathophysiology. Added bidirectional CTD-ME/CFS relationship hypothesis to Chapter 13 (certainty 0.45) with evidence for: (1) CTD predisposition via hypermobility (30-57% in ME/CFS vs 10-15% general population), craniocervical instability, autonomic dysfunction, and mast cell hyperactivity; (2) ME/CFS exacerbation of CTD via ROS-mediated inhibition of prolyl hydroxylases (impairing collagen crosslinking), chronic HIF-1$alpha$ elevation (altering extracellular matrix composition), mast cell activation (MMP-mediated collagen degradation), and basement membrane thickening in capillaries (impairing perfusion). Added HIF-1$alpha$-mediated connective tissue remodeling hypothesis to Chapter 14a (certainty 0.55) linking tendinopathy mechanisms (direct ECM alteration, VEGF-independent pathology, MMP-3-mediated degradation) to ME/CFS connective tissue pathology. Added dysautonomia prevalence data to Chapter 14k: 64% dysautonomia prevalence in chronic musculoskeletal pain (meta-analysis N=1420, RR=2.28 vs controls), POTS comorbidities (31% hypermobility, 36.3% MCAS, 40.9% chronic fatigue), and hEDS/HSD patient experience data (diagnostic delay 19-21 years, 45.6% unemployment). Extended modeling chapters with CTD content: Chapter 27 (HIF-1alpha-ECM coupled model, strain accumulation/PEM threshold), Chapter 28 (mast cell-ECM bistable feedback), Chapter 30 (multi-compartment ECM turnover, HIF-1alpha triad integration), Chapter 31 (ECM degradation temporal trajectory), Chapter 32 (sigmoid CCI-orthostatic severity). Updated hypothesis registry with 2 new entries. _Motivated by:_ @Wirth2026CTDMECFS — preprint proposing bidirectional CTD-ME/CFS relationship and linking ROS, HIF-1$alpha$, mast cell pathways to connective tissue pathology; @Ganesh2024LongCOVIDHSD — hypermobility prevalence data and Long COVID-HSD shared pathophysiology; @Ramirez-Paesano2023CCI — craniocervical instability producing ME/CFS-like symptoms in EDS; @Moschini2026HIFTendinopathy — HIF-1$alpha$ as driver (not marker) of tendinopathy with direct ECM alteration; @Sahin2012HIFTendon — HIF-1$alpha$/VEGF/MMP-3 cascade reducing biomechanical stability; @Almutairi2026DysautonomiaMSD — dysautonomia meta-analysis in chronic musculoskeletal pain; @Kulin2026POTSGI — POTS GI symptoms and comorbidities meta-analysis; @Berg2026HSDSurvey — hEDS/HSD lived experience survey; @Wilson2026hEDSWearable — hEDS wearable monitoring of autonomic dysfunction; @Eccles2021hypermobility — hypermobility prevalence in ME/CFS/FM clinic population.


	- *Cryotherapy and cold exposure for sleep quality* ([Chapter 17, new Section `sec:cold-sleep-warning`; Appendix H, new Section `sec:cold-alternatives`; references.bib, 12 new entries; hypothesis-registry.typ, 2 new entries]): Integration of cryotherapy and cold exposure evidence for sleep quality, pain reduction, and autonomic regulation, with explicit 14 contraindications for ME/CFS patients due to thermoregulatory dysfunction and autonomic instability. Key findings: WBC improves sleep and autonomic function in healthy populations (parasympathetic activation, increased slow-wave sleep, pain reduction) @Douzi2018SleepCryotherapy; ME/CFS patients have documented thermoregulatory dysfunction impairing adaptive responses to cold stress @Li2021ThermoregulationCFS @Cambras2018CircadianCFS; only direct CFS WBC study (Kujawski 2023) showed mixed results with high attrition (45%) @Kujawski2023CBSCFS; cold exposure contraindications for dysautonomia/POTS explicitly listed in safety guidelines @Tipton2017ColdWaterSafety. Home-based alternatives discussed: cold water immersion (10–15°C, 2–5 min, contraindicated for dysautonomia), cold showers (3–5 min, minimal sleep evidence), cold face immersion (safest vagal stimulation option) @Zaproudil2020ColdVagal. _Motivated by:_ User question about ME/CFS hypersensitivity and thermoregulation issues — comprehensive literature review found thermoregulatory dysfunction contraindicates cold exposure without clinical supervision.


