- *Heat and cold thermoregulation integration* ([Chapter 2, autonomic symptoms section updated with ET-1 and heat stroke shared pathway mechanisms; Chapter 3, temperature section expanded with vascular tone dysregulation mechanism; Chapter 6, 3 new speculations: spec:mitochondrial-reserve-thermoreg (cert 0.55), spec:autophagy-switch-heat (cert 0.40), spec:cold-exposure-mitochondrial (cert 0.25); Chapter 9, new speculation spec:dual-oscillator-thermoreg (cert 0.40) on SCN vs peripheral vascular oscillator decoupling; Chapter 10, new speculation spec:vasomotor-constriction-bias (cert 0.45) on tonic vasoconstriction explaining dual heat+cold intolerance and open-question oq:bat-cold-intolerance on BAT activation failure; Chapter 14, new speculation spec:controlled-heat-paradox (cert 0.50) on Waon therapy benefit despite heat intolerance; Chapter 17, new citations added to hyperthermia and ISR sections; Chapter 20, new thermoregulatory biomarkers section with spec:wbh-biomarker (cert 0.35) and oq:thermoreg-composite-biomarker; Appendix H, 4 new annotated entries (Hochecker2025 cert 0.55, Stanculescu2021 cert 0.65, Cambras2023 cert 0.60, Soejima2015 cert 0.50); references.bib, 4 new entries; hypothesis registry, 5 new entries (3 speculations, 2 open-questions); hypotheses-trees/subtrees/heat-cold-thermoregulation.md, new subtree with 90 nodes; hypotheses-trees/hypotheses-trees.md, root index updated; ops/plans/heat-cold-thermoregulation-integration-plan.md, new plan; content-staging/heat-cold-thermoregulation-literature-2026-05-31.md, Phase 1 literature review; content-staging/brainstorm-heat-cold-thermoregulation-2026-05-31.md, Phase 3 brainstorm (90 ideas)]): Comprehensive integration of heat and cold effects on ME/CFS patients with online research. Key mechanistic findings: (1) Hochecker et al. (2025, n=9) demonstrated WBH reduces autophagy (LC3-II minus 17.84%, p=0.0065) and increases mitochondrial respiration (plus 61 to 112%) via HSP70 induction, establishing cellular mechanism for thermal therapy; (2) Stanculescu et al. (2021) identified 9 shared pathways between heat stroke and ME/CFS (gut permeability, endotoxemia, endothelial dysfunction, mitochondrial impairment, HSP deficiency), explaining why heat is disproportionately harmful; (3) Cambras et al. (2023) linked skin temperature circadian disruption to endothelin-1 (p less than 0.01), establishing vascular tone dysregulation as a peripheral thermoregulatory mechanism; (4) Soejima et al. (2015, n=10) showed Waon therapy (far-infrared sauna) significantly reduces fatigue and improves mood with zero adverse events, creating the controlled heat paradox. Five novel mechanistic speculations: mitochondrial spare respiratory capacity as thermoregulatory bottleneck, WBH-induced selective-to-bulk autophagy transition, dual-oscillator circadian thermoregulatory decoupling (central SCN vs peripheral ET-1 oscillator), tonic vasomotor constriction bias explaining dual heat+cold intolerance, and failed BAT activation via sympathetic dysfunction underlying cold intolerance. Clinical implications: thermoneutral water (31 to 32 degrees C) safety premise strengthened; controlled heat therapy (Waon/WBH) research-stage only, requiring heat tolerance screening; composite thermoregulatory dysfunction index (ET-1 plus skin temperature plus mitochondrial reserve) proposed as objective biomarker. Phase 4 integrated 10 hypotheses across 5 chapters. _Motivated by:_ Hochecker2025HyperthermiaMECFS -- first demonstration of cellular-level mitochondrial and autophagy rescue by hyperthermia in ME/CFS; Stanculescu2021HeatStrokeMECFS -- systematic comparison revealing ME/CFS-heat stroke shared vulnerability pathways; Cambras2023SkinTemperatureEndothelin -- ET-1 link providing peripheral vascular mechanism for thermoregulatory failure; Soejima2015WaonTherapyCFS -- clinical pilot establishing safety and potential efficacy of passive heat therapy in CFS.

